  • 7/17/23, 9:41 AM
    Commented on #675 v3.4.0 requires IntoParams for actix path parameter types, breaking newtype pattern from juhaku/utoipa

    @juhaku , your responses here sound like you no longer consider this a bug. The workaround you gave to my case does not solve my case.

    In the route function definition, I have the name of the single path variable : foo_id: Path - this approach means the function signature describes the parameter names.

    This is valid in actix, and I can do any_name_I_like: Path. Your suggestion to use #[into_params(names("custom_uuid"))] means that my valid actix functions are no longer supported by utoipa, because in v3.3.0 I could use the same newtype in multiple functions using different arg names - which is quite normal as a newtype is often only a very thin wrapper around a primitive type, or basic type like uuid. Forcing all newtype to always have the same name in APIs is a very new requirement. For me, it will mean I need to split many of my newtypes into multiple types so this new "one newtype = one API name" constraint can be satisfied. This isnt the end of the world, but deserves fixing or yanking 3.4.0. I'd prefer it was fixed, because I'd prefer utoipa doesnt reject valid actix code, but I'll adjust our codebase if this subset of actix is no longer acceptable.

    • Check sanity of models

    Code Review

    Concerns

    Checklist

    General

    • Does the implementation satisfy the requirements?
    • Beyond linting, is the code easy to read and understand? Are naming choices appropriate, descriptive and consistent with other parts of the system?
    • Is the code tested, and do the tests adequately cover the requirements?
    • Is the code documented?
    • Are there any hard coded configuration items?
    • Is the code tightly coupled to other systems, in a way that would make it difficult to maintain?
    • Is the code using new external libraries, that have not been captured and assessed as part of the SOUP management process?
    • Are there obvious security vulnerabilities; e.g.: use of free text passwords/keys
    • Is there any unnecessary duplication, either within the change, or of an existing module or standard library?
    • Is the data structure choice appropriate?
    • Does the code have any memory leaks? e.g. data structures that are continually added to, but never removed from?
    • Has thought been given to handling of exceptions?
    • Is the logging adequate for debugging in production?

  • 7/16/23, 12:11 AM
    Commented on #348 readOnly support from oxidecomputer/typify

    We have a Rust service which emits JSON. Some of the fields can be written to and sent back to the service, but other fields in the same struct are not writable - one non-writable field is the record identifier, but there are other struct members which we don't support modification. We're using https://github.com/juhaku/utoipa on progenitor emitted structs to build the API.

    Currently we have two schema - the real one and the "writable" one - which is duplication we can remove/automate if we can start using readOnly. We are using the generated structs on both the server and the client, so in our use-case it is simpler if there is a separate "writable" struct, with from/into between the complete and "writable" structs. The downside to this is that if a struct with some readonly members is part of another struct, the containing struct also needs a "writable" struct, etc, etc. In our case there is only two levels, so this is managable.

    If typify was to use skip_serialize on the readonly fields, which makes sense for a client, we would need to remove that with syn, otherwise it would break our actix service code. But we already have ~1000 lines of syn post-processing progenitor's output, so a little more wont hurt. Probably what we would do is use syn to detect however typify is representing the readonly-ness, and split the struct into two:

    1. the server one using serde's skip_deserialize to ensure that even if the incoming JSON has those members it will be stripped before it reaches the endpoint
    2. the client one using serde's skip_serialize so that it doesnt try to send that field. And then some more syn so that the progenitor generated endpoint client code is using the appropriate struct.

    In short, dont worry too much about our use-case. As long as typify does something to represent readonly fields, we'll be happy and use syn to mold the generated code to meet our needs.
